WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.868
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.557 --> 00:00:06.890
DAVID NIHILL: Thanks for coming.

00:00:06.890 --> 00:00:09.190
I didn't think I would
be climbing over people

00:00:09.190 --> 00:00:10.530
to get through the room.

00:00:10.530 --> 00:00:13.030
Somebody must have started a
vicious rumor that Taylor Swift

00:00:13.030 --> 00:00:15.280
was coming here today, not me.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:16.420
She will be around Dublin.

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:18.820
Someone always dodgy is singing
in Dublin when I'm here.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:22.960
The last time I was in
Google, it was Justin Bieber.

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:26.230
So I don't know who's
booking this schedule.

00:00:26.230 --> 00:00:27.910
I do totally hate
public speaking

00:00:27.910 --> 00:00:32.080
and I always have done, and
I know that sounds crazy.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:35.262
My nickname in university
was always Shaking Stevens.

00:00:35.262 --> 00:00:37.720
I don't know if you've had it
when you hold a bit of paper,

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:38.919
or something like this.

00:00:38.919 --> 00:00:40.710
And it's in your hands
and your presenting,

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:42.490
and you're like,
why is it shaking?

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:44.830
Oh, no, and you're
looking around.

00:00:44.830 --> 00:00:46.510
For me, it actually
went through my body

00:00:46.510 --> 00:00:49.250
so much that I became like
an Irish salsa dancer.

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:51.561
It was going
absolutely everywhere.

00:00:51.561 --> 00:00:52.810
And you'll see it happens now.

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:54.280
Can you see it shaking?

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:56.090
Can't control it, so
I just don't do it.

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:57.840
That was one of the
first things I learned

00:00:57.840 --> 00:00:58.930
not to do pretty quickly.

00:00:58.930 --> 00:01:01.090
And for this predicament
did I find myself in,

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:03.147
I blame Americans.

00:01:03.147 --> 00:01:05.230
I don't know if you've
been there or noticed this,

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:08.350
but they're a lot more
positive than Irish people

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:11.200
and they will support you
with anything, no matter

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:12.970
how bad the plan sounds.

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:14.890
You could be like, I'm
going to give up my job

00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:17.170
and sell inflatable
penguins on the internet,

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:17.710
and they'll go like,
(AMERICAN ACCENT)

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:18.709
you should do that, man.

00:01:18.709 --> 00:01:20.260
That could be great.

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:21.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:21.070 --> 00:01:22.780
Sometimes you just
miss Irish people

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:24.880
to tell you that's
a horrible plan.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:26.740
Get those penguins
down off eBay.

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:29.290
You're bringing
shame to the family.

00:01:29.290 --> 00:01:31.930
They would tell you very quickly
that it's not a good idea

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:33.820
to do with your time.

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:36.010
Literally, I was so bad in
the Shaking Stevens days

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:37.718
that when I went to
university originally

00:01:37.718 --> 00:01:39.520
in IT Tallaght and
then later in UCD--

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:42.100
but at IT Tallaght
people in other classes

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:47.110
knew I was so bad that it
was worth coming to see me.

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:48.439
That's a very Irish thing.

00:01:48.439 --> 00:01:50.230
They're like, this is
going to be terrible.

00:01:50.230 --> 00:01:52.339
Let's go see it.

00:01:52.339 --> 00:01:54.130
And I'd be there and
I'd be looking around.

00:01:54.130 --> 00:01:56.465
I'm like, who are those
extra people down the back?

00:01:56.465 --> 00:01:58.900
They're like, they came
to see you go to pieces.

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:01.344
And I was like, oh, man.

00:02:01.344 --> 00:02:03.760
And it kind of got the better
me all through my existence.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:06.400
And it does sound like the worst
plan ever, what I did the end,

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:09.820
was to do stand-up comedy
intensively for a full year

00:02:09.820 --> 00:02:12.040
to try and get over a
fear of public speaking.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:13.640
But I loved Malcolm Gladwell.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:15.140
I don't if you know
him as a writer.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:17.470
And I love Tim Ferriss
and I loved AJ Jacobs,

00:02:17.470 --> 00:02:20.290
and I loved anyone who wrote
about the 80-20 principle.

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:22.030
Basically, all
authors that had said

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:24.550
you could short-cut
learning processes.

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:27.220
There was a way to
do things quickly

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:30.430
and that people who had
mastery in a certain topic

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:32.990
had usually clocked up
about 10,000 hours doing it.

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:35.297
So one thing-- you could
shortcut to a certain level.

00:02:35.297 --> 00:02:37.630
But if you wanted to be a
true master, who would that be

00:02:37.630 --> 00:02:38.710
and what would they do?

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:40.960
So that was Malcolm
Gladwell's 10,000 hours--

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:42.550
that if you looked
at Bill Gates,

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:44.410
or you looked at the Beatles,
or you looked at anyone

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:45.770
who had huge
success in one area,

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:47.228
they usually hit
that 10,000 hours.

00:02:47.228 --> 00:02:50.140
So I was like, well, who's
better at this than anyone

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:52.060
in the world on public speaking?

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:53.596
Surely, it's comedians.

00:02:53.596 --> 00:02:54.970
Like, they're up
there doing this

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:57.554
in the worst of
circumstances every night,

00:02:57.554 --> 00:02:59.470
where people might be
coming in off the street

00:02:59.470 --> 00:03:01.200
after having a horrible day--

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:03.760
depressed, lost their
job, drinking alcohol,

00:03:03.760 --> 00:03:07.697
close their arms, sit there,
and go, make me laugh.

00:03:07.697 --> 00:03:09.530
And you're like, surely,
night after night--

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:11.740
and it turns out comedians,
on average, the ones that

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:14.470
are dedicating themselves, do
it-- put about four hours a day

00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:17.290
between actually being on
stage and crafting the content

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:18.620
to get on stage.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:20.860
And usually, they estimate
it takes about seven years

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:23.500
to make an income full-time
from stand-up comedy, which

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.200
is roughly about
those 10,000 hours.

00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:29.020
And I didn't come across
any of this voluntarily.

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:31.990
A friend of mine tragically
had a spinal cord injury,

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.480
fell from a third story
balcony, and doctors told him

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:35.734
he'd never walk again.

00:03:35.734 --> 00:03:37.150
And he didn't want
to accept that.

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:39.820
And his insurance company
cut him off and wouldn't

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:41.010
fund his recovery attempts.

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:43.010
And all my American friends
were super positive.

00:03:43.010 --> 00:03:44.460
They're like, no, we're going
to get him through this.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:45.610
We're going to do fundraisers.

00:03:45.610 --> 00:03:46.827
We're going to get the money.

00:03:46.827 --> 00:03:48.410
And it kind of rubbed
off on me a bit.

00:03:48.410 --> 00:03:51.429
And I was like, well, maybe
I can do something, as well.

00:03:51.429 --> 00:03:53.470
And I said, well, why
don't we do a charity show?

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:54.490
I know this comedian.

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:55.720
Maybe I can get
him to headline it.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:58.053
He just happens to be my next
door neighbor at the time.

00:03:58.053 --> 00:03:59.070
Maybe he'll do it.

00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:01.040
And I went to my friend Arash
and I said, we should do this.

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:02.200
And he's like, oh,
man, that's great.

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:03.520
You're going to be
the host, right?

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:04.519
You're going to host it?

00:04:04.519 --> 00:04:07.150
I was like, oh, no.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:09.370
He did not know what all
my Irish friends knew

00:04:09.370 --> 00:04:11.710
and all those extra people
in the back of the room in IT

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:14.580
Tallaght you that I was not very
good at that kind of carrying

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:15.080
on.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:17.440
But it gave me a
kind of a reason

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:20.620
to realize the ridiculous
of the fear I had

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:23.014
and it gave me a belief that
maybe you could overcome it.

00:04:23.014 --> 00:04:25.180
And I think I've learned
the hard way after all this

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:28.040
that you never really overcome
a fear of public speaking.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.520
And I think so many people
get sold on the belief

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:31.900
that you will overcome it.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:33.370
Take this 10-step program.

00:04:33.370 --> 00:04:34.210
Take this class.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:35.020
Do this weekend.

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:36.180
You can overcome it.

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:38.500
And everyone I met never
really overcame that fear.

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:40.090
They just learned to manage it.

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:42.460
And that's exactly what
happened to me over time.

00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:44.050
So I started talking
to comedians.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:47.140
I said, right, I wouldn't
describe public speaking

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:47.974
as a crippling fear.

00:04:47.974 --> 00:04:50.223
I was like, my friend's
sitting there in a wheelchair,

00:04:50.223 --> 00:04:52.540
looking at me saying, you're
going to host this thing?

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.270
You can't even consider using
that word in that room anymore.

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:57.740
So I'm like, it's just, look
at what you're going through.

00:04:57.740 --> 00:04:58.780
I'm afraid of speaking.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:00.140
That just makes no sense.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:02.744
And especially when you break
down the term public speaking--

00:05:02.744 --> 00:05:04.410
like, Irish people
hate public speaking,

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:05.576
but imagine going to Irish--

00:05:05.576 --> 00:05:06.946
Irish people love speaking.

00:05:06.946 --> 00:05:09.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:10.380
We love speaking.

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:11.700
We just hate public speaking.

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:12.320
It makes no sense.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:13.560
You're like, do you
like speaking, do you?

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:14.080
Oh, yeah.

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:16.413
Do you ever do it in public,
you talk to people, you do?

00:05:16.413 --> 00:05:17.060
Oh, I do, yeah.

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:18.090
What about public speaking?

00:05:18.090 --> 00:05:18.810
Oh, no, no, no.

00:05:18.810 --> 00:05:20.706
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:20.706 --> 00:05:23.190
But it just has this weird,
very weird thing when

00:05:23.190 --> 00:05:24.536
you put these things together.

00:05:24.536 --> 00:05:26.910
So I was like, right, the time
has come to try, at least,

00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:28.350
and get over this, or manage it.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:29.580
I wanted to do
this charity event.

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:31.288
So I talked to all
the comedians I could.

00:05:31.288 --> 00:05:33.092
I did as much research
as I possibly could.

00:05:33.092 --> 00:05:35.550
I really dived into this and
went way down the rabbit hole.

00:05:35.550 --> 00:05:37.560
Did the charity show--
it went really well.

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:39.507
One of the main comics
thought it went so well

00:05:39.507 --> 00:05:41.340
that he asked me to
open for him at a comedy

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:43.325
club, the main comedy
club in San Francisco.

00:05:43.325 --> 00:05:44.700
And I was like,
should I tell him

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:46.400
I have no idea what I'm doing?

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:49.080
No, so I did it.

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:50.580
And that scared
the life out of me.

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:52.359
And I did it again
and I did it again.

00:05:52.359 --> 00:05:54.150
And I was very much
influenced by an author

00:05:54.150 --> 00:05:57.020
called AJ Jacobs I don't know
if you've read any of his work.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:57.520
I love him.

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.760
He goes into topics
intensively for one year.

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:03.344
So he was a guy who wrote "The
Year of Living Biblically."

00:06:03.344 --> 00:06:05.760
You ever read it, where he
followed the rules of the Bible

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:08.500
to the letter, the law,
even though he was Jewish?

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:10.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:10.460 --> 00:06:11.789
He took it extremely seriously.

00:06:11.789 --> 00:06:13.830
At one stage, he was in
New York in Times Square,

00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:15.510
throwing rocks at adulterers.

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:17.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:19.266
It's a really, really good book.

00:06:19.266 --> 00:06:20.640
So I was like,
right, intensively

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:22.230
for a year-- stand-up comedy.

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:23.867
I can't tell any
of my Irish friends

00:06:23.867 --> 00:06:25.950
this plan because they're
not going to support it.

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:27.270
They're not like
the American ones.

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:29.130
They're going to be
like, what you are doing?

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:30.130
You had your master's degree.

00:06:30.130 --> 00:06:30.780
You're not using it.

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:32.970
You're going to be a comedian
with no intention of being

00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:33.469
a comedian?

00:06:33.469 --> 00:06:35.950
It just makes no
sense long-term.

00:06:35.950 --> 00:06:37.020
But I did it anyway.

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:38.970
And it turned out it's quite
hard to clog up stage time

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:40.750
if people know you don't
know what you're doing,

00:06:40.750 --> 00:06:42.360
so I had to make it look
like I'd been around doing

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:43.152
comedy for a while.

00:06:43.152 --> 00:06:44.693
And nobody in America
could pronounce

00:06:44.693 --> 00:06:46.080
my last name, which is Nihill.

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:47.790
It was a bit unusual
even in Ireland.

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:49.430
So they kept calling
me Irish Dave.

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:51.540
So I was like,
there's a good stage

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:53.910
name that sounds horrendous
all at the same time.

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:56.510
Irish Dave-- so I had to get
Irish Dave a website to make it

00:06:56.510 --> 00:06:59.051
look like he'd been around for
a while and very professional,

00:06:59.051 --> 00:07:00.060
and a Facebook page.

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:01.810
And at the time--
mildly controversial--

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:04.330
but you could go on
Fiverr.com and buy likes.

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:06.890
So Irish Dave was pretty
popular there, for a while.

00:07:06.890 --> 00:07:08.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:10.125
Mostly in India.

00:07:10.125 --> 00:07:11.477
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:11.477 --> 00:07:13.310
That would have been a
real red flag for me,

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:15.726
but Americans, they
seemed OK with it.

00:07:15.726 --> 00:07:17.100
Even the concept,
I was like, why

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.446
would Irish Dave be big in
Ireland for doing comedy?

00:07:19.446 --> 00:07:20.820
That's the worst
stage name ever.

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:23.552
That's like a guy called
American Frank touring America.

00:07:23.552 --> 00:07:25.260
Like, wait, what's
the American part for?

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:26.930
Anyway, nobody questioned it.

00:07:26.930 --> 00:07:29.700
So this got a little bit out
of control and it ended up--

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:31.560
this is at the end
of a full year.

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:34.560
And The Moth is a storytelling
competition in the US.

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:37.080
It's true stories told
live with no notes

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:39.030
and this is the biggest
competition final

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:40.290
they do anywhere in the world.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:41.664
It's in San
Francisco and there's

00:07:41.664 --> 00:07:42.960
1,400 people in the audience.

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:46.257
And that little ant on stage
about to lay an egg is me.

00:07:46.257 --> 00:07:48.090
And if you came up and
hugged me after that,

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:49.715
you'd felt like you
just hugged someone

00:07:49.715 --> 00:07:51.450
who got out of the shower--

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:54.742
not good, not sexy,
not anything like that.

00:07:54.742 --> 00:07:56.200
But if you were to
see me speaking,

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:58.230
you would have thought I looked
pretty comfortable with what

00:07:58.230 --> 00:07:59.190
I was doing.

00:07:59.190 --> 00:08:01.000
I didn't have
butterflies in my chest.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.230
I had pigeons.

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:05.160
It was big and bad
and it was messy,

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:06.480
but other people couldn't tell.

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:10.260
So at this stage, I'd learned to
figure out a way that comedians

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:12.030
knew backwards and
sideways of how

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.610
to manage that public speaking
fear, how to get to a point

00:08:14.610 --> 00:08:16.270
where you know it's
going to go well.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:18.480
It's just a matter of how
well it's going to go,

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:19.890
and that puts you quite at ease.

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:22.110
And it was just all these things
the comedians knew and learned

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:24.000
the hard way, and clocking
up those 10,000 hours

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:25.710
that the average
person, even people who

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:28.164
taught public speaking, didn't
seem to have a clue about.

00:08:28.164 --> 00:08:29.580
And I was like,
it's kind of crazy

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:31.050
that you're ignoring
the one group of people

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.360
who are doing this the most,
especially in the world

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.571
of business, where most people
kind of need it-- no offense.

00:08:36.571 --> 00:08:38.070
Have you been to a
conference lately

00:08:38.070 --> 00:08:39.630
where you're like-- they're
first question is like,

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:40.799
not will I sit near the stage?

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:41.789
It's like, where's the plug?

00:08:41.789 --> 00:08:42.630
Where's the nearest plug?

00:08:42.630 --> 00:08:44.280
Where am I going to
plug-in my laptop?

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:45.600
Where am I going to
plug-in my devices

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:47.016
because this is
going to be boring

00:08:47.016 --> 00:08:48.280
